High selectivity is also an important indicator to determine whether the catalyst can be applied to industry. To simulate the complexity of real oils, naphthalene and p-xylene was added to evaluate the selectivity of the catalyst, respectively. In Fig. 6
                     , the addition of naphthalene or p-xylene did not cause a significant decline in the ability of the catalyst to remove DBT. The ODS performance of CQD/C18PWIL-1 in three aromatic sulfur compounds (DBT, 4-MDBT, 4,6-DMDBT) were investigated (Fig. 7
                     ). The results showed that the target catalyst for different sulfur-containing substrates have excellent desulfurization efficiency. The ODS efficiency was DBT > 4-MDBT > 4,6- DMDBT. The reasonable explanation was the steric hindrance effect caused by more methyl groups in 4-MDBT and 4, 6-DMDBT molecules, leading to the decrease of desulfurization efficiency. In addition, the cyclicity and stability of catalyst under the same conditions was also evaluated (Fig. 8
                     ). The removal efficiency was maintained at 96 % after 18 times of repeated use, the activity decrease after 18 cycles may be pertinent to the coverage of active sites causing by the accumulation of corresponding oxidation products. To prove this assumption, the regeneration experiment and the heat filtration experiment of the recycled catalyst were carried out. As shown in Fig. 8a, the recycled catalyst was regenerated by simple ethanol washing and then applied to the next cycle, the desulfurization efficiency of the regenerated catalyst returned to 97.6 %. As shown in Fig. 8b, after filtrating the catalyst from the reaction system at 15 min, the sulfur removal of DBT was completely interrupted, hot filtration experiment confirming no active species leaching during the ODS process. These experiments directly demonstrated the high stability of the catalyst in the ODS process, excellent cyclicity and stability are more favorable for industrial applications.

In order to further investigate the reactive O species reaction process, several scavengers were added to the catalyst reaction system for free radical trapping experiments (Fig. 10
                     ). As a ·O2– free radical scavenger, the addition of benzoquinone (BQ) did not affect the desulfurization performance of the catalyst. After adding dimethyl sulfoxide (DMSO), the desulfurization activity decreased significantly, indicating that ·OH should be the main reactive O species of the desulfurization process.[48,49] To further verify the active O species produced in this ODS process, electron spin resonance (ESR) was conducted with DMPO as the trapping agent (Fig. 11
                     ). The signals of DMPO - ·OH can be detected in the ESR spectra of the reaction, indicating that the active O species was ·OH. With the same reaction condition, CQD/C18PWIL-1 as catalyst, the ·OH signal intensity generated is much stronger than C18PWIL, demonstrating that the incorporation of CQDs promoted the generation of ·OH. The generation rate of active O species in the ODS process was accelerated, which was further demonstrated due to the incorporation of CQDs improving the utilization rate of H2O2.
